Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.00,0:29:45.36,Default,,0,0,0,,everyone is concerned about the other\Nperson's comfort instance for instance
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.36,0:29:52.79,Default,,0,0,0,,is warm enough in here for you u\Nis the quietude sufficient is you know
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.79,0:29:57.60,Default,,0,0,0,,the acoustics good enough so I am\Nconcerned right now as we talk with your
Dialogue: 0,0:29:57.60,0:30:02.39,Default,,0,0,0,,comfort are you warm enough and did we\Nwarm this room up enough before we got
Dialogue: 0,0:30:02.39,0:30:09.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Am I speaking loud enough to record it?\NSo I'm aware of every instant
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.60,0:30:16.08,Default,,0,0,0,,uh of the overall context of this very\Nmoment
Dialogue: 0,0:30:16.08,0:30:20.96,Default,,0,0,0,,without specifically speaking of it but\NI'm constantly aware of it as a
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.96,0:30:25.36,Default,,0,0,0,,prevailing\Nuh overall conditions the temperature
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.36,0:30:29.67,Default,,0,0,0,,the location the acoustics the place the\Ncameras
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.67,0:30:35.67,Default,,0,0,0,,uh any other witnesses in the room\Nthe loudness of my voice the uh
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.67,0:30:41.60,Default,,0,0,0,,appropriateness of the my verbal\Nresponses to your questions. Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.60,0:30:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,>> So,\N>> and then I'll be either happy or
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.76,0:30:47.91,Default,,0,0,0,,unhappy.\N>> So, if I do poorly, then when this is
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.91,0:30:51.76,Default,,0,0,0,,over, I'll say, well, I could have been\Nmore eloquent. I could have explained
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.76,0:30:55.44,Default,,0,0,0,,that better. You know what I mean?\NThere's no end to the self-criticism
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.44,0:30:59.91,Default,,0,0,0,,that you can indulge in.\NSo, you get to know that that's the
Dialogue: 0,0:30:59.91,0:31:04.39,Default,,0,0,0,,nature of human consciousness.\NEven though you do the best that you
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.39,0:31:09.44,Default,,0,0,0,,can, the mind will always say, "Well,\Nyou could have done better." Holds out
Dialogue: 0,0:31:09.44,0:31:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,the hypothetical,\Nbut after a while, you get smart and you
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.20,0:31:16.79,Default,,0,0,0,,learn the hypothetical. There's only the\Nhypothetical.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.79,0:31:21.03,Default,,0,0,0,,And if it was really real, it it\Nwouldn't have been hypothetical. It
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.03,0:31:24.88,Default,,0,0,0,,would have actually happened.\N>> So, it's kind of like the broken window
Dialogue: 0,0:31:24.88,0:31:28.32,Default,,0,0,0,,theory that, you know, there's one\Nbroken window and then all of a sudden
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.32,0:31:33.27,Default,,0,0,0,,there's another broken window. So\N>> when when people
Dialogue: 0,0:31:33.27,0:31:37.12,Default,,0,0,0,,so they would you say that they attract\Nthat to them?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:37.12,0:31:41.51,Default,,0,0,0,,>> I think that's a good principle. I've\Nforgotten the broken window principle.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:41.51,0:31:45.60,Default,,0,0,0,,>> I'm glad you brought it up that if you\Ndon't take care of things that need
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.60,0:31:50.08,Default,,0,0,0,,repair.\NIt'll bring further detriment. So it is
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.08,0:31:54.64,Default,,0,0,0,,the whole principle of detriment.\N>> That that which is poorly kept and not
Dialogue: 0,0:31:54.64,0:32:01.12,Default,,0,0,0,,cared for will attract to itself other\Ndetriment. Well, you know, such as
Dialogue: 0,0:32:01.12,0:32:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,>> some people that\Num are, you know, they they start off,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:07.44,0:32:11.12,Default,,0,0,0,,you know, smoking marijuana and they\Nadvance to harder drugs and harder drugs
Dialogue: 0,0:32:11.12,0:32:17.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and their life slowly spirals down. It's\Nkind of the same principle, wouldn't you
Dialogue: 0,0:32:17.03,0:32:23.36,Default,,0,0,0,,say, as the broken window theory?\N>> Well, there's a certain similarity.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:23.36,0:32:27.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.\NWhen you start on drugs, you're part of
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.03,0:32:31.12,Default,,0,0,0,,the broken window principle. You go to\Nharder harder drugs.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:31.12,0:32:33.91,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yeah.\N>> I mean, not everybody does that, but
Dialogue: 0,0:32:33.91,0:32:36.48,Default,,0,0,0,,some do.\N>> Many do. Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:36.48,0:32:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,>> So, I would say that, you know, that's\Nkind of the same principle. You attract.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.84,0:32:46.39,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, you attract what likes\Nto you. In other words, if you're a
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.39,0:32:49.91,Default,,0,0,0,,spiritual person, you're going to\Nattract other spiritual people. In daily
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.91,0:32:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,reality, you you like tends to go to\Nlike,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:54.00,0:32:56.64,Default,,0,0,0,,>> right?\N>> That's correct.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:56.64,0:33:00.39,Default,,0,0,0,,In in daily actuality, like tends to go\Nwith like.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:00.39,0:33:07.84,Default,,0,0,0,,>> So, if you were to change one thing in\Nyour life, such as, you know, pray over
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.84,0:33:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,your food or um eat every time before\Nyou eat. Um and uh say a prayer for
Dialogue: 0,0:33:15.20,0:33:19.51,Default,,0,0,0,,mankind at night. And when you get up to\Nthem in the morning, say a prayer that
Dialogue: 0,0:33:19.51,0:33:24.79,Default,,0,0,0,,the day would go well. Um that would\Nchange your whole life then.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:24.79,0:33:27.12,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Well, that\N>> eventually
Dialogue: 0,0:33:27.12,0:33:31.76,Default,,0,0,0,,>> then that that constitutes the quality\Nquality of your life. That's correct.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:31.76,0:33:35.27,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Right.\N>> Uh some people seek perfection at all
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.27,0:33:41.03,Default,,0,0,0,,times as a matter\Nu of a matter of their own reality.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.03,0:33:46.32,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Mhm. I would like to speak as eloquently\Nas I can with you on the couch right at
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.32,0:33:52.48,Default,,0,0,0,,this moment. If we especially if we have\Na camera focused on us, I would like to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:52.48,0:33:58.24,Default,,0,0,0,,be as eloquent as possible.\NExplain things so that could be easily
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.24,0:34:02.08,Default,,0,0,0,,understood.\N>> But what I'm saying is that likes
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.08,0:34:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,attracting likes. In other words, if you\Nbecome more spiritual in your belief
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.44,0:34:11.67,Default,,0,0,0,,system, you're going to attract more\Nspiritual. I think that's true
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.67,0:34:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,>> and if you don't such as the broken\Nwindow theory um then uh you would
Dialogue: 0,0:34:18.32,0:34:22.63,Default,,0,0,0,,attract that to you also\N>> life goes to like
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.63,0:34:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,>> right\N>> so
Dialogue: 0,0:34:24.56,0:34:30.56,Default,,0,0,0,,>> as little magnets then we are shifting\Nyou know and so each day our choices if
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.56,0:34:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,we choose this this is going to happen\Nif we choose that that is going to
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.48,0:34:38.15,Default,,0,0,0,,happen so you want to think about your\Nchoices
Dialogue: 0,0:34:38.15,0:34:46.39,Default,,0,0,0,,>> every day in life so that you know you\Nuh choose the for the better good.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:46.39,0:34:52.39,Default,,0,0,0,,>> You constantly try to choose the the the\Nbest of all the alternatives
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.39,0:34:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,>> last night for reasons I have no idea. I\Nwas unable to sleep
Dialogue: 0,0:34:58.00,0:35:01.92,Default,,0,0,0,,or at least a good part of the night. I\Nwasn't worrying about anything.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.92,0:35:04.96,Default,,0,0,0,,>> No,\N>> I wasn't thinking about anything.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.96,0:35:11.35,Default,,0,0,0,,I wasn't physically annoyed with\Nanything for some mysterious reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:11.35,0:35:16.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh, sleep did just did not arrive. Now,\Nwhy in the world didn't I sleep last
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.80,0:35:20.64,Default,,0,0,0,,night? I wasn't worried. I wasn't\Npreoccupied. I didn't have a pain
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.64,0:35:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,anywhere.\NI didn't have anything to do. Nothing
Dialogue: 0,0:35:24.07,0:35:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,was keeping me up. I didn't have the\Ntelevision on. No distraction.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.35,0:35:36.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So, why in the world was I laying there\Nwide awake for a couple hours?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:36.72,0:35:41.83,Default,,0,0,0,,And I said to myself, why am I lying\Nawake here for a couple hours, not
Dialogue: 0,0:35:41.83,0:35:47.11,Default,,0,0,0,,thinking about anything for no reason?\NAnd you know what?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:47.11,0:35:59.68,Default,,0,0,0,,>> There wasn't any answer.\NThen I realized I'm not going to get an
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.68,0:36:07.76,Default,,0,0,0,,answer. So that was okay. And I said,\Nuh, lots of things happen and and are
Dialogue: 0,0:36:07.76,0:36:12.24,Default,,0,0,0,,what they are,\Nuh, without our understanding it or
Dialogue: 0,0:36:12.24,0:36:19.11,Default,,0,0,0,,knowing the why or the where the what\Nfor of it. It's just the way it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:19.11,0:36:26.24,Default,,0,0,0,,>> So acceptance is an important part also.\N>> Yeah, there you go. to accept uh what
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.24,0:36:31.11,Default,,0,0,0,,>> just however it is at the moment just\Nlike the temperature in this room I
Dialogue: 0,0:36:31.11,0:36:38.56,Default,,0,0,0,,accept whatever it is right now\Nand uh it's satisfactory
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.56,0:36:44.32,Default,,0,0,0,,so I don't know why I didn't get bored\Nwhen I look back at it now I say why
Dialogue: 0,0:36:44.32,0:36:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,wasn't I bored while I was lying there\Nwide awake with nothing to think about
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.72,0:36:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,wasn't making any plans for the day uh I\Nwasn't reminiscing about the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.83,0:37:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh just lying there doing nothing.\NWell, that's major progress, isn't it?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.56,0:37:05.52,Default,,0,0,0,,In a way,\N>> to just lay there and do nothing, it
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.52,0:37:09.11,Default,,0,0,0,,doesn't even bother you that you're\Ndoing nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:09.11,0:37:12.64,Default,,0,0,0,,That sort of rubs the Protestant ethic\Nthe wrong way. You should be doing
Dialogue: 0,0:37:12.64,0:37:18.24,Default,,0,0,0,,something useful at all times,\Neven if you're just serving as an
Dialogue: 0,0:37:18.24,0:37:25.04,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor.\NWell, I have one that goes back into
Dialogue: 0,0:37:25.04,0:37:29.11,Default,,0,0,0,,greed and money and everything. This is\Na question that uh someone wrote in and
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.11,0:37:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,says, "Can you have money and still be\Nspiritual?"
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.35,0:37:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Well, of course, the church proves it.\N>> You're not going to make any brownie
Dialogue: 0,0:37:40.00,0:37:46.16,Default,,0,0,0,,points on that one.\N>> No. You can have all the money in the
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.16,0:37:52.24,Default,,0,0,0,,world and and be spiritual or you can be\Npoor and be spiritual.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.24,0:37:56.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, being poor doesn't necessarily\Nmake you spiritual. You know, people
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.16,0:38:00.07,Default,,0,0,0,,say, well, to be really spiritual, you\Ngot to be, you know, poor, a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.07,0:38:05.83,Default,,0,0,0,,poor. Uh, that doesn't necessarily make\Nyou more spiritual at all. You know,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.83,0:38:09.68,Default,,0,0,0,,>> I know poor poor people who are very\Nspiritual and I know rich people are
Dialogue: 0,0:38:09.68,0:38:14.72,Default,,0,0,0,,very spiritual.\Nuh doesn't seem to have to do with
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.72,0:38:18.96,Default,,0,0,0,,money.\NMoney and social positions seem to be
Dialogue: 0,0:38:18.96,0:38:23.68,Default,,0,0,0,,superficial pertinances.\NYou can live on Fifth Avenue in a
Dialogue: 0,0:38:23.68,0:38:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,multi-million dollar\Num apartment and be very uh spiritual
Dialogue: 0,0:38:32.56,0:38:39.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and uh you can live in poverty right\Nnext to a church and be very vicious.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:39.68,0:38:46.48,Default,,0,0,0,,So it doesn't depend on neighborhood.\N>> So actually it isn't what one has, it's
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.48,0:38:50.16,Default,,0,0,0,,what one is\N>> and what it means to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:50.16,0:38:52.48,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yeah.\N>> What it means to you, the value that you
Dialogue: 0,0:38:52.48,0:38:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,put on it.\N>> Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:54.24,0:39:00.40,Default,,0,0,0,,>> I mean, I value the time that you and I\Nhave together right this moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.40,0:39:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh how often will it recur? I don't\Nknow. We don't know how long life we're
Dialogue: 0,0:39:06.88,0:39:11.28,Default,,0,0,0,,scheduled for.\NSo, I value every moment I have with
Dialogue: 0,0:39:11.28,0:39:16.80,Default,,0,0,0,,you. I value our sitting here on the\Ncouch and talking together.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:16.80,0:39:21.76,Default,,0,0,0,,How do I know that this couldn't be the\Nlast mo few moments of my life? You
Dialogue: 0,0:39:21.76,0:39:29.11,Default,,0,0,0,,know, there could be a loud noise and\Nboth of us vaporize.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:29.11,0:39:32.96,Default,,0,0,0,,I think of it lately because there's a\Nhelicopter that keeps going over our
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.96,0:39:34.32,Default,,0,0,0,,house.\N>> Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:34.32,0:39:38.80,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yeah. There's a airport not far away.\N>> Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:38.80,0:39:42.24,Default,,0,0,0,,>> And for some reason the helicopters go\Nright over our house. So I say
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.24,0:39:45.92,Default,,0,0,0,,everything is peaceful and wonderful and\Nthen I hear
Dialogue: 0,0:39:45.92,0:39:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and it gets louder and louder and\Nlouder.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.88,0:39:57.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And you know the main reason that upsets\Nme is because I know it upsets you.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:57.11,0:40:01.83,Default,,0,0,0,,If if I didn't if I if the helicopters\Ndidn't bother you, I'd pay no attention
Dialogue: 0,0:40:01.83,0:40:06.48,Default,,0,0,0,,to them. But uh I get annoyed because I\Nknow the louder they get, they're going
Dialogue: 0,0:40:06.48,0:40:12.56,Default,,0,0,0,,to be right directly overhead and it's\Ngoing to bother you. So it's not the
Dialogue: 0,0:40:12.56,0:40:16.96,Default,,0,0,0,,helicopter, it's the fact that the\Nhelicopter
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.96,0:40:21.11,Default,,0,0,0,,interferes with your peace of mind and\Nhappiness. That's what I hate about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:21.11,0:40:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yeah.\N>> I have to get out my machine gun and
Dialogue: 0,0:40:23.52,0:40:29.44,Default,,0,0,0,,shoot it down so it stops ruining your\Nhappiness. Right. It's a
Dialogue: 0,0:40:29.44,0:40:34.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a military helicopter that keeps\N>> I don't know what it is. Yeah. Right.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:34.40,0:40:41.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. Right.\N>> That makes it a little tough.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:41.11,0:40:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Well, one part of love is that we want\Neveryone that we love to be happy
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.72,0:40:49.52,Default,,0,0,0,,and so we we try our best to\N>> Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:49.52,0:40:53.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> to fulfill their their needs and and\Nbring about the greatest happiness
Dialogue: 0,0:40:53.83,0:40:58.31,Default,,0,0,0,,possible.\NSo in other words,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.31,0:41:03.44,Default,,0,0,0,,>> um, like you were saying, one could be\Nspiritual and live on Fifth Avenue.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:03.44,0:41:06.80,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yes.\N>> And then, so what it is is that one can
Dialogue: 0,0:41:06.80,0:41:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,be spiritual and live on Fifth Avenue,\Nbut it's the label we put on that.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.00,0:41:18.40,Default,,0,0,0,,>> That's the label we put on. Yes. Cuz\NI've lived on Fifth Avenue and um
Dialogue: 0,0:41:18.40,0:41:21.44,Default,,0,0,0,,had a very exclusive penthouse\Napartment,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:21.44,0:41:28.64,Default,,0,0,0,,>> but it's the label we put on it. and and\NI've also lived in in in semi-poverty
Dialogue: 0,0:41:28.64,0:41:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,>> and I can't say I was necessarily\Nhappier in one condition than the other
Dialogue: 0,0:41:32.56,0:41:38.96,Default,,0,0,0,,tell the truth.\N>> Mhm.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:38.96,0:41:44.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And Department of Truth Avenue\Nand uh and stayed on Long Island all at
Dialogue: 0,0:41:44.31,0:41:50.40,Default,,0,0,0,,the same time.\NMhm.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:50.40,0:41:54.64,Default,,0,0,0,,So you you can have the good things of\Nthe life
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.64,0:41:58.56,Default,,0,0,0,,frankly\Nthey don't make you happy
Dialogue: 0,0:41:58.56,0:42:03.44,Default,,0,0,0,,>> right\N>> but they fulfilled the certain desires
Dialogue: 0,0:42:03.44,0:42:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,and uh they contribute to being content\Nanyway satisfied.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:09.04,0:42:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,If my shoes didn't match today it would\Nfeel a little weird.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:13.59,0:42:18.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh you'll notice they they do match\Ndon't they?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:18.07,0:42:20.48,Default,,0,0,0,,My shoes do mesh today.\N>> Yes,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:20.48,0:42:29.28,Default,,0,0,0,,>> they didn't this morning earlier.\N>> Well, that sometimes happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:29.28,0:42:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,>> They didn't match earlier. No, that's\Ntrue.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:33.92,0:42:36.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Confessions of a married couple.\N>> Yeah,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:36.72,0:42:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,>> the shoes didn't match. Thank God for my\Nwife. Otherwise, they would not be
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.48,0:42:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,matching.\NSo, I thank you that I have matching
Dialogue: 0,0:42:43.83,0:42:48.40,Default,,0,0,0,,shoes today, Susie. It's\N>> so hard to love. So what we have to
Dialogue: 0,0:42:48.40,0:42:53.68,Default,,0,0,0,,learn to do is not judge.\N>> I think there there you're putting it
Dialogue: 0,0:42:53.68,0:42:59.11,Default,,0,0,0,,correctly, huh?\N>> So the lesson is, you know, uh not to
Dialogue: 0,0:42:59.11,0:43:01.76,Default,,0,0,0,,judge.\N>> You know, they always say don't judge a
Dialogue: 0,0:43:01.76,0:43:03.44,Default,,0,0,0,,book by its cover.\N>> Yeah. Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:03.44,0:43:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,>> You know, it's an old saying. I forget\Nwho said that, but
Dialogue: 0,0:43:08.00,0:43:14.48,Default,,0,0,0,,>> it's um so in other words, it's our\Nwe're we're projecting what we think
Dialogue: 0,0:43:14.48,0:43:17.28,Default,,0,0,0,,onto them\N>> onto things. Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:17.28,0:43:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,We're projecting value,\N>> value, prestige. Yeah. Um
Dialogue: 0,0:43:22.24,0:43:25.44,Default,,0,0,0,,>> desiraability.\N>> Desiraability, you know, and so we're
Dialogue: 0,0:43:25.44,0:43:27.52,Default,,0,0,0,,projecting that on to\N>> social image,
